Communicated by:
ProMED-mail
<promed@promedmail.org>

[Good ventilation could be the key to avoiding coronavirus infections as autumn approaches and people spend more time indoors. The use of split air conditioning units that recirculate cooled room air may contribute to the transmission of SARS-CoV-2 (https://wwwnc.cdc.gov/eid/article/26/7/20-0764_article).

Furthermore, the use of a ventilation system to ensure clean air circulation in the home should be coupled with checks of the vent filters as these are not fool-proof. In the US, researchers investigating the Oregon Health & Science University Hospital found that traces of coronavirus were trapped by the filters with some leakage reported. Similarly, in South Korea, a call centre on the 11th floor of an office building had one person infect more than 90 others.

Lessons for indoors, in addition to other precautions such as hand washing and disinfection, adequate ventilation, and air circulation while keeping the indoors comfortable during the cooler weather will be a challenge. - Mod.UBA]

******
[2] Spain: restrictions
Date: Wed 30 Sep 2020 CEST
Source: Reuters [abridged, edited]
https://www.reuters.com/article/idUSL8N2GR76Q


Residents of infection hotspot Madrid are to be barred from leaving except on essential trips under new rules to fight the coronavirus resurgence, Spain's government said on Wednesday [30 Sep 2020].

But regional authorities said the decision had no legal basis, setting the stage for a political showdown in an area accounting for more than 1/3 of Spain's 133 604 new cases in the past 2 weeks.

"Madrid's health is Spain's health. Madrid is special," Health Minister Salvador Illa told a news conference to announce the new regulations, due to come into force in days.

The capital city, with more than 3 million people, and 9 surrounding municipalities with at least 100 000 inhabitants each, are to see borders closed to outsiders for non-essential visits, the government said.

People would be allowed to cross boundaries for work, school, doctors' visits, or shopping, but not for leisure.

Other measures include the closure of bars and restaurants at 11 p.m., from a previous curfew of 1 a.m., as well as shutting parks and playgrounds. Social gatherings will be limited to 6 people.

Madrid has 735 cases per 100 000 people, one of the highest of any region in Europe and double Spain's national rate.

The conservative regional assembly had already enforced localised lockdowns in 45, mostly poor districts, often with a high immigrant population.

But the wider restrictions announced by Illa see the Socialist-led central government override the regional authority after weeks of fighting over what should be done.

Spain has recorded 769 188 cases -- the highest in Western Europe -- and 31 791 deaths.

[Byline: Nathan Allen, Belen Carreno, Ingrid Melander; editing: Angus MacSwan, Kirsten Donovan, Andrew Cawthorne]

